<h1>Problem 416 - 2017 IMOSL, G4, G</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 7</h2>
<p>In triangle \(ABC\), let \(\omega\) be the excircle opposite to \(A\). Let \(D, E\) and \(F\) be the points where \(\omega\) is tangent to \(BC, CA\), and \(AB\), respectively. The circle \(AEF\) intersects line \(BC\) at \(P\) and \(Q\). Let \(M\) be the midpoint of \(AD\). Prove that the circle \(MPQ\) is tangent to \(\omega\).</p>
